t is totally normal to be confused—this is a big jump from a standard "run a script" setup to a "service-based" setup. Let’s break down the terminology and who does what.

1. What is "Browserless"?
   Think of your current setup: your script starts, it opens a "Local Chrome" inside the container, does the work, and then kills the Chrome process when it's done.

Browserless is a special version of Chrome that lives inside a Docker container and stays open. It doesn't run a script; it just "hosts" browser sessions. Instead of your script saying "Launch Chrome," your script says "Connect to the Chrome that is already running at this IP address."

2. What is "Warm"? (The ACA part)
   Cold Start: When you use ACI beginStart(), Azure has to find a computer, download your image, and boot the OS. This is why it takes 60 seconds.

Warm Start: You keep one container running 24/7 (this is the minReplica: 1 setting in Azure Container Apps). Because the container is already "awake," it responds in milliseconds.

ACA (Azure Container Apps): This is just a better version of ACI. It allows you to say, "Keep 1 container running at all times, but if 10 users join at once, automatically spin up 5 more."

3. What is the Debugger URL?
   In your old setup, you used noVNC to "see" the desktop. It was a lot of work to set up.
   Browserless has this feature built-in. It provides a web page (the "Debugger") that lets you see and click inside the browser that your script is currently controlling.

Who makes the URL? The Playwright script (or your backend) simply "knows" it. It’s not a random string; it’s a predictable link based on the userId.

Example: If your service is at sync.myapp.com, the URL is always https://sync.myapp.com/debugger/?id=USER_123.

